475","–1432":"–1432","1495":"1495","1470":"1470","1447":"1447","1479":"1479","1412":"1412","1432":"1432","1498":"1498","1476":"1476","1475":"1475","1431":"1431","1441":"1441","1430":"1430","Abt. 1430":"circa 1430","1428":"1428","1427":"1427","Bescote, Stafford, England":"Bescot, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ludlow, Shropshire, England":"Ludlow, Shropshire, England","Bescot, Staffordshire, England":"Bescot, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1432–1447":"1432–1447","1427–1479":"1427–1479","1430–1476":"1430–1476","1430–1495":"1430–1495","1431–Male":"1431–Deceased","1428–1470":"1428–1470","1441–1498":"1441–1498","1412–1475":"1412–1475","–1432":"–1432","1495":"1495","1470":"1470","1447":"1447","1479":"1479","1412":"1412","1432":"1432","1498":"1498","1476":"1476","1475":"1475","1431":"1431","1441":"1441","1430":"1430","Abt. 1430":"about 1430","1428":"1428","1427":"1427","Bescote, Stafford, England":"Bescot, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Ludlow, Shropshire, England":"Ludlow, Shropshire, England","Bescot, Staffordshire, England":"Bescot, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"MOUNTFORT","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Mountford  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mountford","meanings":["English (Staffordshire; of Norman origin): habitational name from Montfort-sur-Risle (Eure) or from one or other of various places called Montfort in France (from Old French <i>mont</i> ‘hill’ + <i>fort</i> ‘fortress’). Early forms of this name are indistinguishable from those of Mundford in Norfolk, perhaps indicating an alternative habitational name (see   Munford  ).","History: A Norman bearer of this name, from Montfort-sur-Risle in Eure, near Brionne, accompanied William the Conqueror in his invasion of England in 1066. Simon <i>de Montfort</i>, 6th Earl of Leicester, led a rebellion against Henry III (1216–1272)."]}]},{"name":"Lord","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   Lorraine   or variant spelling of   Laurie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lorraine","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, in origin denoting a migrant from the province of <i>Lorraine</i> in eastern France. This derives its name from Latin <i>Lotharingia</i> ‘territory of the people of <i>Lothar</i>’. The latter is a Germanic personal name derived from <i>hlud</i> ‘fame’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. <i>Lorraine</i> began to be used as a girl's name in Scotland in the 19th century, and for a time in the second half of the 20th century enjoyed great popularity, which has since waned."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Lord Robert MOUNTFORT was born in 1432, in Bescot, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Sir Baldwin Mountfort and Jo